import pandas as pd  

# Load dataset and convert Timestamp to datetime  
df = pd.read_csv("Data.csv")  
df["Timestamp"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Timestamp"], errors="coerce")  

# Filter data for 2018 at the specified station  
df = df[(df["Timestamp"].dt.year == 2018) &  
        (df["station"] == "Lal Bahadur Shastri Nagar, Kalaburagi - KSPCB")].dropna(subset=["PM2.5"])  

# Categorize seasons based on months  
def classify_season(month):  
    return "Winter" if month in [12, 1, 2] else "Summer" if month in [3, 4, 5] else "Monsoon" if month in [6, 7, 8, 9] else None  

df["Season"] = df["Timestamp"].dt.month.map(classify_season)  

# Remove rows outside defined seasons  
df = df.dropna(subset=["Season"])  

# Compute average PM2.5 per season and find the most polluted one  
seasonal_avg = df.groupby("Season")["PM2.5"].mean()  
worst_season, max_pm25 = seasonal_avg.idxmax(), seasonal_avg.max()  

# Print results  
print("Average PM2.5 per season in 2018:\n", seasonal_avg)  
print(f"\nMost polluted season: {worst_season}")  
print(f"Highest average PM2.5: {max_pm25}")

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load dataset and convert Timestamp to datetime
df = pd.read_csv("Data.csv")
df["Timestamp"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Timestamp"], errors="coerce")

# Filter data for 2021 at the specified station, removing missing PM2.5 values
df = df[(df["Timestamp"].dt.year == 2021) &  
        (df["station"] == "Lal Bahadur Shastri Nagar, Kalaburagi - KSPCB")].dropna(subset=["PM2.5"])

# Categorize days as Weekday or Weekend
df["DayType"] = df["Timestamp"].dt.weekday.map(lambda x: "Weekend" if x >= 5 else "Weekday")

# Compute monthly average PM2.5 for weekdays and weekends
monthly_avg = df.groupby([df["Timestamp"].dt.month, "DayType"])["PM2.5"].mean().unstack()

# Plot PM2.5 trends for weekdays and weekends
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(monthly_avg.index, monthly_avg["Weekday"], marker='o', linestyle='-', label="Weekdays", color='b')
plt.plot(monthly_avg.index, monthly_avg["Weekend"], marker='s', linestyle='--', label="Weekends", color='r')

# Customize plot appearance
plt.xlabel("Month")
plt.ylabel("Average PM2.5 Levels")
plt.title("Monthly Average PM2.5 Levels (Weekdays vs. Weekends) - 2021")
plt.xticks(range(1, 13), ["Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May", "Jun", "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", "Oct", "Nov", "Dec"])
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)

# Show plot
plt.show()

#1.
import pandas as pd

# Load dataset and convert Timestamp to datetime
df = pd.read_csv("Data.csv")
df["Timestamp"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Timestamp"], errors="coerce")

# Filter for 2022 and drop missing PM2.5 or state values
df = df[df["Timestamp"].dt.year == 2022].dropna(subset=["PM2.5", "state"])

# Define months for each season
season_map = {3: "Summer", 4: "Summer", 5: "Summer", 
              6: "Monsoon", 7: "Monsoon", 8: "Monsoon", 9: "Monsoon"}

# Assign season labels based on months
df["Season"] = df["Timestamp"].dt.month.map(season_map)

# Keep only Summer and Monsoon data
df = df.dropna(subset=["Season"])

# Compute state-wise average PM2.5 for each season
avg_pm25 = df.groupby(["state", "Season"])["PM2.5"].mean().unstack()

# Calculate percentage difference: ((Monsoon - Summer) / Summer) * 100
avg_pm25["% Change"] = ((avg_pm25["Monsoon"] - avg_pm25["Summer"]) / avg_pm25["Summer"]) * 100

# Identify state with the highest absolute change
most_varied_state = avg_pm25["% Change"].abs().idxmax()
max_change = avg_pm25.loc[most_varied_state, "% Change"]

# Print results
print("State with the highest percentage change in PM2.5 between Monsoon and Summer (2022):")
print(f"{most_varied_state} with a change of {max_change:.2f}%")

State with the highest percentage change in PM2.5 between Monsoon and Summer (2022):
Assam with a change of -61.18%

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load dataset and parse timestamps
df = pd.read_csv("Data.csv")
df["Timestamp"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Timestamp"], errors="coerce")

# Extract Delhi's data from 2017 to 2023, dropping missing PM2.5 values
delhi_df = df[(df["state"] == "Delhi") & df["Timestamp"].dt.year.between(2017, 2023)].dropna(subset=["PM2.5"])

# Define season mapping
season_mapping = {12: "Winter", 1: "Winter", 2: "Winter",
                  3: "Summer", 4: "Summer", 5: "Summer",
                  6: "Monsoon", 7: "Monsoon", 8: "Monsoon", 9: "Monsoon"}

# Assign seasons and remove undefined months (October & November)
delhi_df["Season"] = delhi_df["Timestamp"].dt.month.map(season_mapping)
delhi_df = delhi_df.dropna(subset=["Season"])

# Compute seasonal averages by year
seasonal_pm25 = delhi_df.groupby([delhi_df["Timestamp"].dt.year, "Season"])["PM2.5"].mean().unstack()

# Plot seasonal trends with different colors
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(seasonal_pm25.index, seasonal_pm25["Winter"], marker='o', linestyle='-', label="Winter", color='blue')
plt.plot(seasonal_pm25.index, seasonal_pm25["Summer"], marker='s', linestyle='--', label="Summer", color='orange')
plt.plot(seasonal_pm25.index, seasonal_pm25["Monsoon"], marker='^', linestyle='-.', label="Monsoon", color='green')

# Labels and title
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Average PM2.5 Levels")
plt.title("Delhi Seasonal PM2.5 Trends (2017-2023)")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)

# Display the plot
plt.show()

#3.
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the dataset
data_file = "Data.csv"  # Adjust path if necessary
pollution_df = pd.read_csv(data_file)

# Convert Timestamp to datetime
pollution_df["Timestamp"] = pd.to_datetime(pollution_df["Timestamp"], errors="coerce")

# Extract Year-Month for analysis
pollution_df["Year-Month"] = pollution_df["Timestamp"].dt.to_period("M")

# Compute average PM2.5 per month for each city
monthly_avg_pm25 = pollution_df.groupby(["Year-Month", "city"])["PM2.5"].mean().unstack()

# Convert PeriodIndex to string for plotting
monthly_avg_pm25.index = monthly_avg_pm25.index.astype(str)

# Plot PM2.5 trends
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(monthly_avg_pm25.index, monthly_avg_pm25["Delhi"], label="Delhi", color="crimson", linestyle="-", marker="o", alpha=0.8)
plt.plot(monthly_avg_pm25.index, monthly_avg_pm25["Mumbai"], label="Mumbai", color="royalblue", linestyle="--", marker="s", alpha=0.8)

plt.xlabel("Year", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("PM2.5 (µg/m³)", fontsize=12)
plt.title("PM2.5 Trends: Delhi vs Mumbai (2015-2023)", fontsize=14)
unique_years = sorted(pollution_df["Timestamp"].dt.year.dropna().unique())
plt.xticks([f"{year}-01" for year in unique_years], unique_years, rotation=45, fontsize=10)
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True, linestyle="--", alpha=0.5)
plt.show()

# Calculate standard deviation of PM2.5 for Delhi & Mumbai
delhi_std = pollution_df[pollution_df["city"] == "Delhi"]["PM2.5"].std()
mumbai_std = pollution_df[pollution_df["city"] == "Mumbai"]["PM2.5"].std()

# Print standard deviation results
print(f"PM2.5 Fluctuation (Std Dev):")
print(f"- Delhi: {delhi_std:.2f} µg/m³")
print(f"- Mumbai: {mumbai_std:.2f} µg/m³")

PM2.5 Fluctuation (Std Dev):
- Delhi: 84.55 µg/m³
- Mumbai: 37.74 µg/m³

#1.
import pandas as pd

# Load datasets
state_file = "State_data.csv"
pollution_file = "Data.csv"

# Read state-wise population data
state_data = pd.read_csv(state_file)

# Read monitoring station data
pollution_data = pd.read_csv(pollution_file)

# Standardize column names
state_data.rename(columns={"State": "state", "Population": "population"}, inplace=True)
pollution_data.rename(columns={"station": "monitoring_station", "state": "state"}, inplace=True)

# Count unique monitoring stations per state
station_summary = pollution_data.groupby("state")["monitoring_station"].nunique().reset_index()
station_summary.columns = ["state", "total_stations"]

# Merge with state population data
combined_data = pd.merge(station_summary, state_data, on="state")

# Calculate monitoring stations per million people
combined_data["stations_per_million"] = (combined_data["total_stations"] / combined_data["population"]) * 1e6

# Find the state with the highest station density
top_state = combined_data.loc[combined_data["stations_per_million"].idxmax()]

# Print results
print("\nState with the highest monitoring stations per million people:")
print(top_state)

#2.
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# File paths
population_file = "State_data.csv"
air_quality_file = "Data.csv"

# Load datasets
population_data = pd.read_csv(population_file)
air_quality_data = pd.read_csv(air_quality_file)

# Standardize column names
population_data.rename(columns={"State": "state", "Population": "population"}, inplace=True)
air_quality_data.rename(columns={"state": "state", "PM2.5": "pm25", "station": "monitoring_site"}, inplace=True)

# Convert Timestamp to datetime format
air_quality_data["Timestamp"] = pd.to_datetime(air_quality_data["Timestamp"], errors='coerce')

# Filter data for the year 2023
data_2023 = air_quality_data[air_quality_data["Timestamp"].dt.year == 2023]

# Drop rows where PM2.5 or state is missing
cleaned_2023_data = data_2023.dropna(subset=["pm25", "state"])

# Calculate average PM2.5 for each state
avg_pm25_by_state = cleaned_2023_data.groupby("state")["pm25"].mean().reset_index()

# Merge with population data
statewise_pm25 = pd.merge(avg_pm25_by_state, population_data, on="state")

# Compute per capita PM2.5 exposure (PM2.5 per million people)
statewise_pm25["pm25_per_million"] = statewise_pm25["pm25"] / (statewise_pm25["population"] / 1e6)

# Select top 5 most polluted states based on per capita PM2.5 exposure
top_polluted_states = statewise_pm25.nlargest(5, "pm25_per_million")

# Plot the bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.bar(top_polluted_states["state"], top_polluted_states["pm25_per_million"], color='crimson')

# Labels and title
plt.xlabel("State")
plt.ylabel("Per Capita PM2.5 Exposure (µg/m³ per million)")
plt.title("Top 5 Most Polluted States in 2023 (Per Capita PM2.5 Exposure)")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define file paths
population_file = "State_data.csv"  
pollution_file = "Data.csv"  

# Load datasets
population_data = pd.read_csv(population_file)
pollution_data = pd.read_csv(pollution_file)

# Rename columns for consistency
population_data.rename(columns={"State": "region", "Population": "total_population", "Area (km2)": "land_area"}, inplace=True)
pollution_data.rename(columns={"state": "region", "PM2.5": "pm25_level", "station": "monitoring_station"}, inplace=True)

# Convert timestamp column to datetime format
pollution_data["Timestamp"] = pd.to_datetime(pollution_data["Timestamp"], errors="coerce")

# Remove rows with missing PM2.5 values or state information
cleaned_pollution = pollution_data.dropna(subset=["pm25_level", "region"])

# Compute average PM2.5 concentration per state
avg_pm25_per_state = cleaned_pollution.groupby("region")["pm25_level"].mean().reset_index()

# Calculate population density (individuals per km²)
population_data["density"] = population_data["total_population"] / population_data["land_area"]

# Merge air pollution data with population density data
combined_data = pd.merge(avg_pm25_per_state, population_data, on="region")

# Generate scatter plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.scatter(combined_data["density"], combined_data["pm25_level"], color="darkorange", alpha=0.7)

# Labels and title
plt.xlabel("Population Density (people per km²)")
plt.ylabel("Average PM2.5 Concentration (µg/m³)")
plt.title("Impact of Population Density on PM2.5 Levels")
plt.grid(True, linestyle="--", alpha=0.5)

# Display the plot
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

pollution_data = pd.read_csv("Data.csv")
state_data = pd.read_csv("State_data.csv")

state_data.rename(columns={"State": "state", "Population": "population", "Area (km2)": "area"}, inplace=True)

pollution_data.rename(columns={"state": "state"}, inplace=True)
cleaned_pollution = pollution_data.dropna(subset=["PM2.5"])

avg_pm25_per_state = cleaned_pollution.groupby("state")["PM2.5"].mean().reset_index()

merged_data = pd.merge(avg_pm25_per_state, state_data, on="state")
merged_data["pm25_density"] = merged_data["PM2.5"] / merged_data["area"]
sorted_pm25_density = merged_data.sort_values(by="pm25_density", ascending=False)
most_polluted = sorted_pm25_density.iloc[0]["state"]
print(f"State with the highest PM2.5 concentration per square kilometer: {most_polluted}")

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.bar(sorted_pm25_density["state"], sorted_pm25_density["pm25_density"], color="darkred")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.xlabel("States")
plt.ylabel("PM2.5 Density (µg/m³ per km²)")
plt.title("PM2.5 Concentration per Square Kilometer by State")
plt.grid(True, linestyle="--", alpha=0.5)

plt.show()

#3.
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load datasets
states_data = pd.read_csv("State_data.csv")
pollution_data = pd.read_csv("Data.csv")

# Convert date column
pollution_data["Timestamp"] = pd.to_datetime(pollution_data["Timestamp"], errors="coerce")

# Filter data for 2021 and selected states
filtered_data = pollution_data[
    (pollution_data["Timestamp"].dt.year == 2021) & 
    (pollution_data["state"].isin(["Maharashtra", "Madhya Pradesh"]))
]

# Compute average PM2.5 per state
avg_pm25 = filtered_data.groupby("state")["PM2.5"].mean().reset_index()

# Extract required state information
state_details = states_data[states_data["State"].isin(["Maharashtra", "Madhya Pradesh"])][["State", "Population", "Area (km2)"]]

# Calculate population density
state_details["Density"] = state_details["Population"] / state_details["Area (km2)"]

# Merge PM2.5 data
merged_data = state_details.merge(avg_pm25, left_on="State", right_on="state").drop(columns=["state"])

# Display table
print(merged_data)

# Plot population density and PM2.5 levels
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 5))

ax1.bar(merged_data["State"], merged_data["Density"], color="steelblue", label="Population Density")
ax1.set_ylabel("Population Density (people/km²)", color="blue")
ax1.tick_params(axis="y", labelcolor="blue")

ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.plot(merged_data["State"], merged_data["PM2.5"], color="crimson", marker="o", linestyle="-", label="PM2.5 Levels")
ax2.set_ylabel("Avg PM2.5 (µg/m³)", color="red")
ax2.tick_params(axis="y", labelcolor="red")

plt.title("Population Density vs PM2.5 Levels (2021)")
fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

#1.
import pandas as pd

funding_info = pd.read_csv("NCAP_Funding.csv")
pollution_data = pd.read_csv("Data.csv")

# Standardize column names
funding_info.rename(columns={"State": "state"}, inplace=True)
pollution_data.rename(columns={"state": "state", "PM2.5": "PM25"}, inplace=True)

# Convert timestamps to datetime format
pollution_data["Timestamp"] = pd.to_datetime(pollution_data["Timestamp"], errors="coerce")

# Extract data for 2021
pollution_2021 = pollution_data[pollution_data["Timestamp"].dt.year == 2021].dropna(subset=["PM25", "state"])

# Mark states that received NCAP funding
funded_states = set(funding_info["state"])
pollution_2021["Funding_Status"] = pollution_2021["state"].apply(lambda state: "Funded" if state in funded_states else "Not Funded")

# Compute the average PM2.5 levels for funded vs non-funded states
pm25_comparison = pollution_2021.groupby("Funding_Status")["PM25"].mean()

# Display results
print("\nAverage PM2.5 Levels in 2021 (Funded vs Non-Funded States):")
print(pm25_comparison)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
pollution_data = pd.read_csv("Data.csv")
funding_data = pd.read_csv("NCAP_Funding.csv")

# Filter data for Assam
assam_pollution = pollution_data[pollution_data["state"] == "Assam"].copy()
assam_pollution["Timestamp"] = pd.to_datetime(assam_pollution["Timestamp"])

# Compute average PM2.5 levels over time
assam_pm25_trend = assam_pollution.groupby("Timestamp")["PM2.5"].mean().reset_index()

# Extract Assam’s funding details
assam_funding = funding_data[funding_data["State"] == "Assam"].copy()
funding_years = {
    "Amount released during FY 2019-20": "2019-04-01",
    "Amount released during FY 2020-21": "2020-04-01",
    "Amount released during FY 2021-22": "2021-04-01",
}

# Convert funding data to numeric
for col in funding_years.keys():
    assam_funding[col] = pd.to_numeric(assam_funding[col], errors="coerce")

# Summarize funding amounts by year
assam_funding_summary = (
    assam_funding[list(funding_years.keys())]
    .sum()
    .reset_index()
    .rename(columns={"index": "Year", 0: "Funding Amount"})
)

# Map column names to actual dates
assam_funding_summary["Year"] = assam_funding_summary["Year"].map(funding_years)
assam_funding_summary.dropna(inplace=True)
assam_funding_summary["Year"] = pd.to_datetime(assam_funding_summary["Year"])

# Create a dual-axis plot
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))

# PM2.5 trend line
ax1.plot(assam_pm25_trend["Timestamp"], assam_pm25_trend["PM2.5"], color="red", label="PM2.5 Levels")
ax1.set_xlabel("Year")
ax1.set_ylabel("PM2.5 (µg/m³)", color="red")
ax1.tick_params(axis="y", labelcolor="red")

# NCAP Funding scatter plot
ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.scatter(assam_funding_summary["Year"], assam_funding_summary["Funding Amount"], color="blue", label="NCAP Funding", marker="o", s=100)
ax2.set_ylabel("NCAP Funding (Cr)", color="blue")
ax2.tick_params(axis="y", labelcolor="blue")

# Title and legend
plt.title("PM2.5 Trends & NCAP Funding in Assam")
ax1.legend(loc="upper left")
ax2.legend(loc="upper right")

plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# File paths
state_data_path = "State_data.csv"
funding_data_path = "NCAP_Funding.csv"

# Load datasets
state_df = pd.read_csv(state_data_path)
funding_df = pd.read_csv(funding_data_path)

# Standardize column names
state_df.rename(columns={"State": "state", "Area (km2)": "area"}, inplace=True)
funding_df.rename(columns={"State": "state"}, inplace=True)

# Sum total funding for each state across all years
funding_columns = [
    "Amount released during FY 2019-20",
    "Amount released during FY 2020-21",
    "Amount released during FY 2021-22"
]

# Convert funding columns to numeric
for col in funding_columns:
    funding_df[col] = pd.to_numeric(funding_df[col], errors='coerce')

# Calculate total funding received by each state
state_funding = funding_df.groupby("state")[funding_columns].sum().reset_index()
state_funding["Total_Funding"] = state_funding[funding_columns].sum(axis=1)

# Merge area data with funding data
merged_df = pd.merge(state_funding[["state", "Total_Funding"]], state_df[["state", "area"]], on="state")

# Create a scatter plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
scatter = sns.scatterplot(
    x=merged_df["area"],
    y=merged_df["Total_Funding"],
    hue=merged_df["state"],
    palette="tab10",
    s=100,
    edgecolor="black"
)

# Labels and title
plt.xlabel("Area (km²)")
plt.ylabel("Total NCAP Funding (Crores)")
plt.title("Scatter Plot: State Area vs. NCAP Funding")

# Move legend outside the plot
plt.legend(title="State", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc="upper left")

# Show the plot
plt.show()

import pandas as pd

# Load dataset
data_df = pd.read_csv("Data.csv")

# Standardize column names
data_df.rename(columns={"PM2.5": "PM25", "city": "City"}, inplace=True)

# Convert 'Timestamp' to datetime format
data_df["Timestamp"] = pd.to_datetime(data_df["Timestamp"], errors='coerce')

# Filter data for the year 2023
data_2023 = data_df[data_df["Timestamp"].dt.year == 2023].dropna(subset=["PM25", "City"])

# Identify the city with the highest average PM2.5 levels
most_polluted_city = data_2023.groupby("City")["PM25"].mean().idxmax()

# Extract data for the most polluted city
city_pollution_data = data_2023[data_2023["City"] == most_polluted_city]

# Calculate total recorded days and hazardous days (PM2.5 > 300 µg/m³)
total_days = city_pollution_data["Timestamp"].dt.date.nunique()
hazardous_days = city_pollution_data[city_pollution_data["PM25"] > 300]["Timestamp"].dt.date.nunique()
hazardous_percentage = (hazardous_days / total_days) * 100

# Display results
print(f"Most Polluted City in 2023: {most_polluted_city}")
print(f"Total Days Recorded: {total_days}")
print(f"Hazardous Days (PM2.5 > 300 µg/m³): {hazardous_days}")
print(f"Percentage of Hazardous Days: {hazardous_percentage:.2f}%")

#2.
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load dataset
data_path = "Data.csv"
df = pd.read_csv(data_path)

# Clean and standardize column names
df.rename(columns={"PM2.5": "PM25", "state": "State", "Timestamp": "Date"}, inplace=True)

# Convert Date column to datetime format
df["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Date"], errors='coerce')

# Filter data for Delhi (2018-2020)
delhi_pm25 = df[(df["State"] == "Delhi") & (df["Date"].dt.year.between(2018, 2020))].copy()

# Extract Year-Month for trend analysis
delhi_pm25["Year-Month"] = delhi_pm25["Date"].dt.to_period("M")

# Define festival months (Diwali: Oct-Nov, New Year: Dec-Jan)
festival_months = {10: "Diwali", 11: "Diwali", 12: "New Year", 1: "New Year"}

# Label festival periods
delhi_pm25["Festival"] = delhi_pm25["Date"].dt.month.map(festival_months).fillna("Regular")

# Compute monthly average PM2.5 levels
monthly_trends = delhi_pm25.groupby(["Year-Month", "Festival"])["PM25"].mean().reset_index()

# Convert Year-Month to datetime for visualization
monthly_trends["Year-Month"] = monthly_trends["Year-Month"].astype(str)
monthly_trends["Year-Month"] = pd.to_datetime(monthly_trends["Year-Month"])

# Plot PM2.5 trends
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(monthly_trends["Year-Month"], monthly_trends["PM25"], marker="o", linestyle="-", color="blue", label="PM2.5 Levels")

# Highlight festival months
festivals = monthly_trends[monthly_trends["Festival"] != "Regular"]
for _, row in festivals.iterrows():
    plt.annotate(row["Festival"], 
                 xy=(row["Year-Month"], row["PM25"]), 
                 xytext=(row["Year-Month"], row["PM25"] + 20), 
                 arrowprops=dict(facecolor="red", arrowstyle="->"),
                 fontsize=10, color="red")

# Labels and formatting
plt.xlabel("Year-Month")
plt.ylabel("Average PM2.5 (µg/m³)")
plt.title("PM2.5 Trends in Delhi (2018-2020) - Festival Impact")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(True, linestyle="--", alpha=0.5)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd

# Load NCAP funding data
funding_data = pd.read_csv("NCAP_Funding.csv")

# Convert funding values for FY 2020-21 to numeric, replacing "-" with 0
funding_data["Amount released during FY 2020-21"] = pd.to_numeric(
    funding_data["Amount released during FY 2020-21"].replace("-", 0), errors="coerce"
)

# Calculate total funding received by each state in 2020-21
state_funding = funding_data.groupby("State")["Amount released during FY 2020-21"].sum()

# Determine the state that received the highest funding
top_funded_state = state_funding.idxmax()
print("Highest Funded State:", top_funded_state)

# Load air pollution dataset
pollution_data = pd.read_csv("Data.csv")

# Convert timestamp column to datetime format
pollution_data["Timestamp"] = pd.to_datetime(pollution_data["Timestamp"], errors="coerce")

# Extract data for the highest-funded state
state_pollution = pollution_data[pollution_data["state"] == top_funded_state].copy()

# Extract year and compute the yearly average PM2.5 levels
state_pollution["Year"] = state_pollution["Timestamp"].dt.year
yearly_pm25_avg = state_pollution.groupby("Year")["PM2.5"].mean()

# Focus on data from 2020 to 2023
yearly_pm25_avg = yearly_pm25_avg.loc[2020:2023]

# Plot the trend of PM2.5 levels over the years
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(yearly_pm25_avg.index, yearly_pm25_avg.values, marker="o", linestyle="-", color="blue", label="PM2.5 Levels")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Average PM2.5 (µg/m³)")
plt.title(f"Yearly Average PM2.5 Levels in {top_funded_state} (2020-2023)")
plt.grid(True, linestyle="--", alpha=0.6)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Display yearly PM2.5 values
print(yearly_pm25_avg)

Breathing Trouble: The Reality for Students in Polluted Cities¶

For students in Delhi, Mumbai, and Kolkata, simply stepping outside means inhaling air filled with harmful pollutants—equivalent to smoking multiple cigarettes daily. But what’s often overlooked is that indoor spaces like classrooms, libraries, and dorms aren’t much safer. Poor ventilation traps pollutants inside, making it even harder to escape the effects of toxic air.

Why This Matters: Should universities create clean air zones on campuses? Does pollution affect focus, memory, and academic performance? Can stricter air quality policies protect students and workers in high-risk areas? If these cities are shaping future leaders and professionals, shouldn’t clean air be a basic right, not a luxury?
